\description{
Computes HSIC-based sensitivity indices (Da Veiga, 2015) for each
input parameter against each output. By default returns first-order
indices only; \code{total_order = TRUE} adds the complementary total-order
decomposition.
}
\details{
\strong{First-order index} (always computed):
\deqn{S^{HSIC}_j = \frac{HSIC(X_j, Y)}{\sqrt{HSIC(X_j, X_j) \cdot HSIC(Y, Y)}}}{
      S_j^HSIC = HSIC(X_j, Y) / sqrt(HSIC(X_j, X_j) * HSIC(Y, Y))}
is the direct contribution of \code{X_j} to \code{Y} -- analogous to (but not
equal to) the Sobol first-order index.

\strong{Total-order index} (when \code{total_order = TRUE}):
\deqn{T^{HSIC}_j = 1 - \frac{HSIC(X_{\sim j}, Y)}{\sqrt{HSIC(X_{\sim j}, X_{\sim j}) \cdot HSIC(Y, Y)}}}{
      T_j^HSIC = 1 - HSIC(X_(-j), Y) / sqrt(HSIC(X_(-j), X_(-j)) * HSIC(Y, Y))}
where \verb{X_\{~j\}} is the parameter design with column \code{j} removed. By
construction the difference \code{T_j - S_j} captures the contribution of
\code{X_j} \emph{through interactions} with other parameters. For purely
additive models \code{T_j = S_j}; in the presence of interaction
\code{T_j > S_j}.

Unlike variance-based Sobol indices, both versions of the
HSIC-Sensitivity Index capture non-linear and distributional
effects: a parameter that affects the variance, skewness, or tail
of \code{Y} without shifting its mean is invisible to Sobol but visible
to HSIC. The normalisation bounds each index to \verb{[0, 1]}.
}
\section{Relationship to Sobol indices}{

The HSIC-Sensitivity Index is a \emph{dependence screen}, not a variance
decomposition, and it is \strong{not a drop-in substitute for a Sobol
index}. A Sobol index apportions the variance of \code{Y}; the HSIC index
measures how strongly \code{X_j} and \code{Y} are statistically dependent under
the chosen kernels. Because the two answer different questions, their
\emph{rankings} of the inputs need not agree -- and on a function with a
strong additive-versus-interaction contrast they often will not. On
the Ishigami function, for instance, \code{X_2} carries the largest
first-order variance while \code{X_1} carries the strongest overall
dependence (it drives both a main effect and the \code{X_1}-\code{X_3}
interaction), so the HSIC ranking and the variance-based ranking
differ by construction, not by error. Use the HSIC index when the goal
is to detect \emph{any} statistical influence -- on the mean, variance,
skewness, or tail of \code{Y} -- and to screen a large parameter set for
dependence. When the goal is specifically to apportion output variance
(a first/total-order variance budget), use a variance-based estimator
such as \code{sensitivity::sobolEff()} or \code{sensitivity::soboljansen()}; do
not read an HSIC ranking as a Sobol ranking.

Optional permutation p-values are computed for first-order indices
(Benjamini-Hochberg-adjusted across the grid by default).

\strong{Total-order uncertainty quantification (\code{total_order_ci = TRUE},
since 0.0.0.9013).} A pair-bootstrap percentile CI on the index
\code{T_j} itself: resample \verb{(theta, y)} pairs with replacement
\code{n_bootstrap} times, recompute \code{T_j} on each resample, report a
\code{ci_level} (default 95\%) two-sided percentile interval. This is
uncertainty quantification, not a hypothesis test.

\strong{Total-order conditional-permutation significance test
(\code{total_order_test = "cond_perm"}, since 0.0.0.9014).} Tests
\verb{H_0: X_j _||_ Y | X_\{~j\}} -- under the null, \code{X_j} adds nothing
beyond what is already in \verb{X_\{~j\}} and \code{T_j} is concentrated at
zero. The null is generated by \strong{conditional permutation}:
k-means-cluster the design points by \verb{X_\{~j\}} similarity, then
within each cluster permute \code{Y}; recompute \code{T_j} on each permuted
design. p-value \verb{= (1 + #\{T_perm >= T_obs\}) / (1 + B)}. The
\code{p_adjust} method applies grid-wide.

The 0.0.0.9012 \code{total_order_p_value} pair-bootstrap implementation
was \strong{not} this -- it sampled the empirical joint, not a
null-of-no-effect, and was retracted in 0.0.0.9013. The
0.0.0.9014 conditional-permutation test repopulates
\code{p_value_total_order} with a properly-calibrated value; the
\code{total_order_test} flag on the result distinguishes the new mode
from the retracted one.

\strong{Power caveat (empirical calibration 2026-05-16).} Repeated-seed
calibration (\code{orchestra_calibration_20260516.R}, B = 100, N = 80)
confirms the cond_perm test is null-calibrated (per-parameter
type-I rates 0.01-0.04 at nominal alpha = 0.05) but \strong{conservative
on additive designs} (rejection rate ~3\% on a strong-additive
design where the first-order test rejects above 90\%). The reason
is structural: on additive \verb{Y = sum_j f_j(X_j)}, the conditional
permutation of \code{Y} within \verb{X_\{~j\}} bins preserves all of
\verb{X_\{~j\}}'s contribution and randomises only the \code{X_j} component
(which is independent of \verb{X_\{~j\}}), so the permuted
\verb{HSIC(X_\{~j\}, Y_perm)} is statistically close to the observed
\verb{HSIC(X_\{~j\}, Y)}. Use cond_perm for \strong{interaction detection};
use the first-order permutation \code{p_value} (always computed when
\code{p_value = TRUE}) for \strong{additive contributions}. The two are
complementary, not interchangeable.

Total-order CIs cost \code{B * p * q} kernel re-evaluations on resampled
designs; set \code{n_bootstrap} accordingly. Use the CI for honest
uncertainty bars on the index magnitude; do not interpret it as a
significance verdict.
}

\examples{
\donttest{
set.seed(1)
n <- 80L
theta <- matrix(stats::runif(n * 3L), nrow = n,
                dimnames = list(NULL, c("active", "weak", "inert")))
y <- 2 * theta[, "active"] +
     0.5 * theta[, "weak"] +
     stats::rnorm(n, sd = 0.1)
fit <- hsic_sensitivity(theta, y, total_order = TRUE,
                        n_permutations = 199L, seed = 1L)
fit
}

}
